        "text": "\"you have to shove them all into an array\" \u2014 Well, painter's algo is just one solution; a z-buffer remembering the depth of previously painted pixels _can_ truely allow drawing in any order, as you encouter them in the code.  And by deciding per-pixel it avoids issues like <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Painter%27s_algorithm#Cyclical_overlapping|occlusion cycles>.\nSure that doesn't \"eliminate state\", I added a whole-frame buffer!  But conceptually I think of it as a much smaller departure than \"record, sort, replay\".\n\nPedagogically I wouldn't get into either of this until the student (1) understands occlusion and paint order (2) feels that re-ordering code themselves (painter's algo being run in programmer's head not computer) got frustrating...",
        "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
        "thread_ts": "1719876061.824169",
        "parent_user_id": "UCUSW7WVD",
        "blocks": [
